rComments: I loved this prof! Professor Henderson's lectures were heavy and sometimes it felt like if you missed something you could get lost, but for the majority of the time I followed along. The content was dense but incredibly interesting. It's clear that Prof. Henderson has a passion for the material. The grades were made up of two essays and one test.

Graded by 2 essays and an exam. I did all three of them over the course of 3 days and somehow managed to get a very good grade. His lectures are rapid, monotonous and confusing. He's very messy with how he organises the course. If you're interested in content, don't take this course, find a better prof.

Brilliant prof and lecturer. While participation doesn't count, and you can get by without attending class, his lectures are so insightful and interesting and helpful for essay-writing. Keep in mind essays are also about 80% of your final grade. Henderson is an expert in modernist works, so if you're interested in the genre I highly recommend him!
Great professor, one of the best in the department. Charismatic, but you need patience to understand why he's great at what he does.

Good professor, very nice and easily approachable. He does not provide dates for the readings but sends emails to help keep students on track. Very considerate with schedules and willing to help when asked.

Professor Henderson assumes that everyone in his class already has a knowledge of his subject (for me, Rhetoric).  He often sounds like he is speaking down to his students.  He is highly repetitive, but speaks quickly and quietly, so if you do not get a seat near the front, there is really no point in being there.  He is unclear about assignments.
teacherRatingTags: ['Lecture heavy', "Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Tough grader']

rComments: syllabus was unorganized, the course lacked focus - we were analyzing readings to no particular end, Henderson needs to ask the class if they have any questions once in awhile, the expectations and grading are fuzzy

The syllabus was somewhat disorganized because there were no dates, but the professor was hilarious and easy-going.  Oddly enough, we did not have to read anything other than the text-book, even if they were on the syllabus.

Hilarious and easy-going professor. Disorganized syllabus with no dates, though.  However, grading seems somewhat arbitrary. All of my markedly different assignments received the exact same mark. I'm not complaining, since I still received an A, but their limited marking variation was most likely done to make their lives easier.
Content was difficult and his lectures were hard to understand, but the grading isn't bad. For what it is, he does a pretty good job.

I was really excited for this class going into it. The syllabus was the first issue...it had no dates, which was an issue which continued into the lectures where we jumped around a lot. Making notes for this class were also difficult as many times it was hard to catch what he was saying. The lack of structure is what was wrong.

Complaints about Henderson's dryness are unfounded. He does not use powerpoint, audio, a charismatic method of delievery, or create some rediculous incentive to participate when 98% of the class couldn't have an insightfull thought on the material to save their lives, but compensates for this with an often over looked aspect of a lecture: content

He's extremely knowledgeable and goes in-depth with every text and brings up interesting points. Gives a lot of readings though and doesn't provide a detailed time frame for each, so you're literally jumping from novel to novel in a single lecture. In terms of lecturing, couldn't catch/understand what he was saying a lot of the time.
Henderson is very knowledgeable about literature and his "asides" are quite comical. I really enjoyed his class and actually developed a liking for literature because of him.

Personable; delivers lectures well w/ a mixture of textbook knowledge/general academic consensus as well as personal opinions. Had difficulty taking notes because he reads off notes speedily w/o explanation (containing references which I don't understand/can't catch). Will answer Qs though but only if you ask. Marks fairly.

So knowledgeable and helpful. Very easygoing. Doesn't require attendance or participation. Doesn't hold your hand through the subject, but expects you to be responsible with regards to your workload. Treats you like an adult.
beautiful, thorough man

what can i say about henderson? you either love him or you hate him. very boring, but brings up interesting points. he is very knowledgable but this is affected by the fact that he reads off of a paper for the entire lecture. let's just say i would prefer to go out for a beer with the guy over listening to a lecture.
This guy is sort of like Terry Eagleton: good show!

Henderson is my inspiration. I leave his class with thoughts swarming in my head, and sitting in his lectures are what I look forward to in every week. Very insightful, helpful, interesting, has a great sense of humour... I understand his classes may be appealing to a certain taste in literature but he manages to grab attention and maintain it.
Sometimes boring and dry, but lack of slides or media gave an accuse to listen closely instead of copying anything down. Had many funny anecdotes.

He has a great sense of humour, and he's a really nice guy--but sometimes he forgets he's talking to students instead of fellow colleagues. Very hard marker, and his lectures can be tough to follow, but he has some good insights into critical theory.

Attendance at the end of the year was quarter of that at the start. Henderson was hard to follow with no visual aids, and his useful insights lost in his poorly structured lectures. He repeated himself from week to week (in an unhelpful way), and rare class involvement involved fishing for trivial factoids or quotations among the students.

Unfortunately no slides, or anything else to illustrate the lecture is used. However, I found the class to be very informative and the prof. very approachable. The T.A was also nice but a VERY hard marker. I would let this course pass.
In his own world, does not care about making class interesting for students. Stands in one spot for 2 hours and talks, unbearable.

THE WORST! I dont understand where any of you are coming from. i had him in first year and he was UNBEARABLE. absolutely, 100%, worst teacher out there. Didn't TEACH anything...just felt like he sits up there and reads an essay he wrote. WORST. i repeat, WORST. FIRE HIM. Class size shrinks every week...BAD BAD BAD.
He is the worst prof I have ever had in my life! Do not i repeat DO NOT take any class with him!!!
Awesome!
funny and laidback, but unapproachable
One of the best in the department. Intelligent, knowledgable, witty, helpful. You can't go wrong with Professor Henderson!
Had him in first year (Lit for our time) and he was much better then. Still, if you miss a class, he's bound to repeat what he said the next class. Overall, we get to know a lot about his family. :P

A manly intellect, Dr. Henderson acknowledges the **** endemic to a number of his anecdotes. When they fail to illuminate, they still manage to induce unending laughter: a fellow of infinite jest. U of T needs more profs like the H-Bomb.

I really enjoyed his lectures and his teaching style.  I took it during my first year, and he is stil one of my all-time favorite prof.'s.  His style of lecture was great--to the point and precise.  He has an excellent ability to deliver to a large audience.  His lectures were stimulating and insightful.  Loved that class.

I took his class a few years ago as a freshman.  He was a decent professor, although his tendency to pepper his lectures with odd, vaguely bitter asides about his failed literary dreams ("...I'm 10 years older than Conrad was when he published his first book, *sigh*...") was unsettling.
His choice of TA's could have been better.  However, the class seemed at times to drag on, and he was kinda boring
He will de-automatize your perception.

The negative reviews from first-year students are clearly more a reflection of them than Prof. Henderson.  His courses are well-planned and challenging.  He is tolerant, inclusive and warm in the classroom.  He speaks with eloquence and expertise.
Yes this is a boring class, but it's perfect because you don't have to actually go to class and you can end up with a decent mark.  Just go to tutorial, that's all you need to do!
Meh.  He was disposable, his TAs were indespensible.  He's not nearly as amusing as he thinks he is.

Terrible and boring. Was an old drinking buddy of one of my high school teachers (when he was a TA for Henderson) Lectures stink- too much Freudian, psychoanalytic crap that first year students don't need to know or understand. Stay away from Lit for our
Nice guy, usually well-prepared, always willing to chat. Soooo repetitive, though...
BORING!!!  Dropped the class because it was so dreadful.

Brilliant man; funny, too.  Class was always a pleasure to go to - fell asleep in class once (only because I was WAY too tired to be out of bed and Con Hall makes me sleepy anyways) and felt bad about it, because he's great.
Nice enough guy, but he repeats his key points too many times, and the early hour doesn't help matters.  Sped through the poetry section of the class.
First term was good, talked directly about text, tends to ramble, and a lot of pointless blabber, has interesting points, but most classes seem to be boring and pointless
No Comments
lectures are boring and useless, which is why I don't go... should be rating my TA!
Obviously brilliant and has a sense of humor! He's a terrific Prof!
No Comments
Nice. His repetition of points from one lecture to another make napping a must.
intelligent, super nice; his letter of reference got me into grad school
you got to be kidding!  are you people even english students?  grieg's the b
